From: Paul Philippov <paul@themactep.com>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 19:30:00 -0400
Subject: [PATCH] block in poll() instead of busy-polling the input device

process_events() used a non-blocking read followed by usleep(10ms) in
an endless loop: 100 wakeups and ~300 syscalls per second forever, even
when no button is ever pressed. On a single-core camera SoC this is
constant scheduler churn that keeps the CPU from staying idle.

Block in poll() on the event fd instead - the input layer wakes us
exactly when a key event arrives. The 10ms tick is only kept while a
TIMED_FIRE countdown is armed (between press and release/fire), which
is the only case that needs time-based polling. Steady-state wakeups
drop from 100/s to zero with no functional change:

- PRESS/RELEASE/TIMED actions are event-driven and fire on the poll
  wakeup itself;
- TIMED_FIRE keeps its 10ms firing granularity while armed;
- poll() EINTR falls through to the existing EAGAIN-tolerant read.

Signed-off-by: Paul Philippov <paul@themactep.com>

--- a/thingino-button.c
+++ b/thingino-button.c
@@ -11,6 +11,7 @@
 #include <signal.h>
 #include <sys/stat.h>
 #include <ctype.h>
+#include <poll.h>
 
 #define CONFIG_FILE "/etc/thingino-button.conf"
 #define DEFAULT_DEVICE "/dev/input/event0"
@@ -315,8 +316,23 @@
 void process_events(int fd) {
 	struct input_event ev;
 	struct timeval press_times[256] = {{0, 0}};
+	struct pollfd pfd;
+	int poll_timeout = -1;
 
 	while (1) {
+		// Block until an input event arrives instead of busy-polling.
+		// The previous read + usleep(10ms) cycle woke up 100 times per
+		// second forever, even with no button ever pressed. A 10ms tick
+		// is only needed while a TIMED_FIRE countdown is armed; otherwise
+		// sleep in poll() until the input layer delivers an event.
+		pfd.fd = fd;
+		pfd.events = POLLIN;
+		int pn = poll(&pfd, 1, poll_timeout);
+		if (pn < 0 && errno != EINTR) {
+			perror("Error polling event device");
+			break;
+		}
+
 		char buf[16];
 		int n = read(fd, buf, sizeof(buf));
 		if (n == 16) {
@@ -398,6 +414,7 @@
 		// Check for timed fire events
 		struct timeval now;
 		gettimeofday(&now, NULL);
+		int pending_fires = 0;
 		for (int i = 0; i < 256; i++) {
 			for (int j = 0; j < timed_fires[i].count; j++) {
 				TimedFireEntry *entry = &timed_fires[i].entries[j];
@@ -410,11 +427,14 @@
 					log_message("TIMED_FIRE command for key %d: %s (elapsed %f seconds)\n", i, entry->config->command, elapsed);
 					execute_command(entry->config->command);
 					entry->active = 0; // Deactivate the entry after execution
+				} else {
+					pending_fires = 1; // Countdown still armed
 				}
 			}
 		}
 
-		usleep(10000); // Sleep for 10ms to reduce CPU usage
+		// Tick at 10ms only while TIMED_FIRE countdowns are pending
+		poll_timeout = pending_fires ? 10 : -1;
 	}
 }
 
